Chapter One
Kolon
Itanian time, 4:30 a.m. Kolon hated getting up so early. Mainly because he was responsible for waking up the rest of the platoon. He silently got out of bed, put on his combat suit, strapped on his assault vest, packed up his things from the closet, and carefully picked up a small special box. He slung his rifle over his shoulder and hung his helmet on a small hook on his belt. The helmet was equipped with a full set of gear, including a respirator, goggles, and other necessary items. After checking his ammunition pouch, he quietly left the barracks, his boots crunching on the muddy and icy ground.
He pulled out a lighter from his jacket pocket and then took out a cigarette from another pocket. After lighting the cigarette, he took a light puff and then opened the door. Over the past week, he had to strain his brain to wake up his subordinates. He no longer used the preset alarm clock, because half the time it didn't go off, and only a faint hiss could be heard from the speaker.
"Time to wake them up?" Kolon turned around and saw Lieutenant Nemici approaching.
"Yes," Kolon replied.
"What method are you going to use this time?"
Kolon hadn't even had time to reply when the door opened and Harris, Cress, and a few others rushed out, already dressed and ready.
"Good morning," Cress said.
"What woke you up?" Kolon asked.
"First of all, we really don't want to see what method you're going to use today to wake everyone up. Second, the first squad to wake up gets priority for breakfast," a soldier named Ravek replied. "You know how bad that breakfast is."
"you're right, sergeant Ravek," Kolon said. He reached out and pressed the switch. A shrill alarm immediately filled the barracks. He heard someone shouting loudly inside, accompanied by a commotion of hurried footsteps.
"Good heavens, Valturi," Nemici said. "I thought they would have learned by now to get up with you."
"My brothers from basic training did just that," Kolon said, pointing at Harris, Cress, and Ravek. "But to be fair, their squad leader and platoon leader both knew to get up before the soldiers."
A few seconds later, the rest of the platoon ran out. They were all dressed and ready. Some of the new recruits looked drowsy, while others appeared very annoyed.
"Good morning, everyone," Kolon said cheerfully.
"Excuse me, sir, but why did you wake us up that way?" a squad member (corporal) asked.
"Because those regular alarm clocks are just junk. And Daybreak never sleeps in," Kolon said.
"Take your personal belongings," Kolon continued. As a lieutenant and deputy commander of the platoon, he had the responsibility to assist Captain Boradin Shaw, the platoon leader, in supervising and leading the platoon. "We won't be returning. Sergeants and lieutenants, you and your men have fifteen minutes to conduct your final checks and bring along your rations for today."
Members of Exodus platoon quickly dispersed. They were part of the 2nd Shock Division of the Second Army Group. Before their merger, they had originally been two separate platoons, Cohort and Dagger. This was an elite platoon, and Kolon felt a complex mix of emotions about being promoted to lieutenant, there were many reasons for this.
Kolon walked shoulder to shoulder with First Squad leader Nemici along the well-lit base road, where the lights along both sides were powered by generators. Most of the lights were red, helping them avoid enemy bombers. To counter them, Daybreak had begun employing "Wildcat" tactics in both the air and on the ground.
"A new day, a new mission for the Hellbreakers," Nemici said with a dry laugh. "Where exactly are they going to send us this time?"
"An outlying front base near Iarnlos City. We've been sent to support the ground assault." Kolon said, taking a puff of his cigarette. He somewhat resented Cress for getting him hooked on cigarettes, but thinking back on the past year filled with countless battles, he let it go, so he said nothing.
"That's unfortunate. The front lines are really stretched thin," Nemici said in a low voice. "All the news coming out of here is about 'supporting the war, aiding the Kurgan front,' why not support the Howlan front for a change?"
" Well said, brother." Kolon said, flicking the cigarette butt into the mud. "We're going with the First Armored Platoon, no walking involved. Captain Shaw should be there."
"Captain Shaw had us take the vehicle?" Nemici asked, somewhat surprised.
"Yes. To be honest, he isn't as bad as I imagined. I mean, he's not great, but he's not annoying either."
Kolon raised his thumb and index finger, pressing them against the microphone at his throat, and shifted his backpack onto his back. "All units of Exodus, assemble at the West Yard after completing your tasks. We will depart at 05:00 with the First Armored Platoon."
Every few seconds, he received responses from the squad leaders. When they first arrived, Harris, Cress, and Ravek were all junior sergeants. Since their basic training on Earth, the four of them had remained close friends. Kolon felt as though he had known them for a long time, although it had been less than two years. They were all squad leaders, but since the previous platoon leader was hit by a Daybreak sniper and had to retire due to injuries a week ago, Cress had begun leading the second squad.
As they approached the vehicle yard, Kolon and Nemici's eyes fell upon approximately eight Chronos main battle tanks and four Stryker armored vehicles. Crew members scurried about, ensuring their war machines were in proper working order. Kolon quickly spotted Captain Boradin Shaw among the crowd, who was engaged in conversation with the armored platoon commander. As they approached, Captain Shaw glanced at them and came forward to meet them, his usually impassive face showing no emotion.
"Lieutenant Nemici... Lieutenant Varturi..." he said, Kolon slowed his pace. Captain Shaw glanced at Kolon's holstered pistol and then looked up. "The platoon should be ready by now, I suppose?"
